<ENAMEX TYPE="PER_DESC">workers</ENAMEX> and the <ENAMEX TYPE="PER_DESC">stockholders</ENAMEX> are <ENAMEX TYPE="PER_DESC">victims</ENAMEX>. The truth is probably some
combination of these <NUMEX TYPE="CARDINAL">three stylized</NUMEX> scenarios. So, if <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Texaco</ENAMEX> has indeed
discriminated against <ENAMEX TYPE="PER_DESC">blacks</ENAMEX> (and it's worth noting that the evidence for that
proposition is shaky, but I'll accept it for the sake of argument), it's quite
likely that <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Texaco</ENAMEX>'s <ENAMEX TYPE="PER_DESC">stockholders</ENAMEX> have borne most of the cost.

            If <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Texaco</ENAMEX> <ENAMEX TYPE="PER_DESC">executives</ENAMEX> had
indulged their personal tastes for <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Van Gogh</ENAMEX> oil paintings at a
